# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gas-sensors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] A **carbon dioxide sensor** or **CO2 sensor** is an instrument for the measurement of carbon dioxide gas.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] The most common principles for CO2 sensors are infrared gas sensors (NDIR) and chemical gas sensors.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] Measuring carbon dioxide is important in monitoring indoor air quality, the function of the lungs in the form of a capnograph device, and many industrial processes.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] NDIR sensors are spectroscopic sensors to detect CO2 in a gaseous environment by its characteristic absorption.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] The key components are an infrared source, a light tube, an interference (wavelength) filter, and an infrared detector.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] The gas is pumped or diffuses into the light tube, and the electronics measure the absorption of the characteristic wavelength of light.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] NDIR sensors are most often used for measuring carbon dioxide.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] The best of these have sensitivities of 20–50 PPM.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] Typical NDIR sensors cost in the (US) $100 to $1000 range.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] They are used to comply to building standards that focus on wellbeing such as WELL V2.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] Carbon dioxide sensors such as RoomYou1 are used to comply with building standards that prioritize occupant well-being, such as WELL Building Standard.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] NDIR CO2 sensors are also used for dissolved CO2 for applications such as beverage carbonation, pharmaceutical fermentation and CO2 sequestration applications.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] In this case they are mated to an ATR (attenuated total reflection) optic and measure the gas *in situ*.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] New developments include using microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) IR sources to bring down the costs of this sensor and to create smaller devices (for example for use in air conditioning applications).
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] Another method (Henry's Law) also can be used to measure the amount of dissolved CO2 in a liquid, if the amount of foreign gases is insignificant.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] CO2 can be measured using photoacoustic spectroscopy.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] Concentration of CO2 can be measured by subjecting a sample to pulses of electromagnetic energy (such as from a distributed feedback laser) that is tuned specifically to the absorption wavelength of CO2.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] With each pulse of energy, the CO2 molecules within the sample will absorb and generate pressure waves via the photoacoustic effect.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] These pressure waves are then detected with an acoustic detector and converted to a usable CO2 reading through a computer or microprocessor.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] Chemical CO2 gas sensors with sensitive layers based on polymer- or heteropolysiloxane have the principal advantage of very low energy consumption, and that they can be reduced in size to fit into microelectronic-based systems.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] On the downside, short and long term drift effects, as well as a rather low overall lifetime, are major obstacles when compared with the NDIR measurement principle.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] Most CO2 sensors are fully calibrated prior to shipping from the factory.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] Over time, the zero point of the sensor needs to be calibrated to maintain the long term stability of the sensor.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] Furthermore, inasmuch as ventilation is a factor in the spread of respiratory viruses, CO2 levels are a rough metric for COVID-19 risk; the worse the ventilation, the better for viruses and *vice versa*.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] Sensors for these substances can be made using cheap (~$20) Microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) metal oxide semiconductor (MOS) technology.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] The reading they generate is called estimated CO2 (eCO2) or CO2 equivalent (CO2eq).
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] Although the readings tend to be good enough in the long run, introducing non-respiration sources of VOC or CO2, such as peeling fruits or using perfume, will undermine their reliability.
[src:gas-sensors/carbon-dioxide-sensor] H2-based sensors are less susceptible as they are more specific to human breathing, although the very health conditions the hydrogen breath test is set to diagnose will also disrupt them.
[src:gas-sensors/catalytic-bead-sensor] A **catalytic bead sensor** is a type of sensor that is used for combustible gas detection from the family of gas sensors known as pellistors.
[src:gas-sensors/catalytic-bead-sensor] The catalytic bead sensor consists of two coils of fine platinum wire each embedded in a bead of alumina, connected electrically in a Wheatstone bridge circuit.
[src:gas-sensors/catalytic-bead-sensor] One of the pellistors is impregnated with a special catalyst which promotes oxidation whilst the other is treated to inhibit oxidation.
[src:gas-sensors/catalytic-bead-sensor] Current is passed through the coils so that they reach a temperature at which oxidation of a gas readily occurs at the catalysed bead (500-550 °C).
[src:gas-sensors/catalytic-bead-sensor] Passing combustible gas raises the temperature further which increases the resistance of the platinum coil in the catalysed bead, leading to an imbalance of the bridge.
[src:gas-sensors/catalytic-bead-sensor] This output change is linear, for most gases, up to and beyond 100% LEL, response time is a few seconds to detect alarm levels (around 20% LEL), at least 12% oxygen by volume is needed for the oxidation.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] A **chemiresistor** is a material that changes its electrical resistance in response to changes in the nearby chemical environment.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Chemiresistors are a class of chemical sensors that rely on the direct chemical interaction between the sensing material and the analyte.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] The sensing material and the analyte can interact by covalent bonding, hydrogen bonding, or molecular recognition.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Several different materials have chemiresistor properties: semiconducting metal oxides, some conductive polymers, and nanomaterials like graphene, carbon nanotubes and nanoparticles.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Typically these materials are used as partially selective sensors in devices like electronic tongues or electronic noses.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] A basic chemiresistor consists of a sensing material that bridges the gap between two electrodes or coats a set of interdigitated electrodes.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] The resistance between the electrodes can be easily measured.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] The sensing material has an inherent resistance that can be modulated by the presence or absence of the analyte.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] During exposure, analytes interact with the sensing material.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] These interactions cause changes in the resistance reading.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] In some chemiresistors the resistance changes simply indicate the presence of analyte.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] In others, the resistance changes are proportional to the amount of analyte present; this allows for the amount of analyte present to be measured.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] As far back as 1965 there are reports of semiconductor materials exhibiting electrical conductivities that are strongly affected by ambient gases and vapours.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] However, it was not until 1985 that Wohltjen and Snow coined the term *chemiresistor*.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] The chemiresistive material they investigated was copper phthalocyanine, and they demonstrated that its resistivity decreased in the presence of ammonia vapour at room temperature.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] In recent years chemiresistor technology has been used to develop promising sensors for many applications, including conductive polymer sensors for secondhand smoke, carbon nanotube sensors for gaseous ammonia, and metal oxide sensors for hydrogen gas.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] The ability of chemiresistors to provide accurate real-time information about the environment through small devices that require minimal electricity makes them an appealing addition to the internet of things.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Chemiresistors can be made by coating an interdigitated electrode with a thin film or by using a thin film or other sensing material to bridge the single gap between two electrodes.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Electrodes are typically made of conductive metals such as gold and chromium which make good ohmic contact with thin films.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] In both architectures, the sensing material controls the conductance between the two electrodes; however, each device architecture has its own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Interdigitated electrodes allow for a greater amount of the film's surface area to be in contact with the electrode.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] This allows for more electrical connections to be made and increases the overall conductivity of the system.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Interdigitated electrodes with finger sizes and finger spacing on the order of microns are difficult to manufacture and require the use of photolithography.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Larger features are easier to fabricate and can be manufactured using techniques such as thermal evaporation.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Both interdigitated electrode and single-gap systems can be arranged in parallel to allow for the detection of multiple analytes by one device.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Metal oxide chemiresistor sensors were first commercialized in 1970 in a carbon monoxide detector that used powdered SnO2.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] However, there are many other metal oxides that have chemiresistive properties.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Metal oxide sensors are primarily gas sensors, and they can sense both oxidizing and reducing gases.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] This makes them ideal for use in industrial situations where gases used in manufacturing can pose a risk to worker safety.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Sensors made from metal oxides require high temperatures (200 °C or higher) to operate because, in order for the resistivity to change, an activation energy must be overcome.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] In comparison to the other materials graphene chemiresistor sensors are relatively new but have shown excellent sensitivity.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Graphene is an allotrope of carbon that consists of a single layer of graphite.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] It has been used in sensors to detect vapour-phase molecules, pH, proteins, bacteria, and simulated chemical warfare agents.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] The first published report of nanotubes being used as chemiresistors was made in 2000.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Since then there has been research into chemiresistors and chemically sensitive field effect transistors fabricated from individual single-walled nanotubes, bundles of single-walled nanotubes, bundles of multi-walled nanotubes, and carbon nanotube–polymer mixtures.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] It has been shown that a chemical species can alter the resistance of a bundle of single-walled carbon nanotubes through multiple mechanisms.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Carbon nanotubes are useful sensing materials because they have low detection limits, and quick response times; however, bare carbon nanotube sensors are not very selective.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] They can respond to the presence of many different gases from gaseous ammonia to diesel fumes.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Carbon nanotube sensors can be made more selective by using a polymer as a barrier, doping the nanotubes with heteroatoms, or adding functional groups to the surface of the nanotubes.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Many different nanoparticles of varying size, structure and composition have been incorporated into chemiresistor sensors.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] The most commonly used are thin films of gold nanoparticles coated with self-assembled monolayers (SAMs) of organic molecules.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] The SAM is critical in defining some of the nanoparticle assembly's properties.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Firstly, the stability of the gold nanoparticles depends upon the integrity of the SAM, which prevents them from sintering together.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Secondly, the SAM of organic molecules defines the separation between the nanoparticles, e.g. longer molecules cause the nanoparticles to have a wider average separation.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] The width of this separation defines the barrier that electrons must tunnel through when a voltage is applied and electric current flows.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Thus by defining the average distance between individual nanoparticles the SAM also defines the electrical resistivity of the nanoparticle assembly.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Finally, the SAMs form a matrix around the nanoparticles that chemical species can diffuse into.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] As new chemical species enter the matrix it changes the inter-particle separation which in turn affects the electrical resistance.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Analytes diffuse into the SAMs at proportions defined by their partition coefficient and this characterizes the selectivity and sensitivity of the chemiresistor material.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Conductive polymers such as polyaniline and polypyrrole can be used as sensing materials when the target interacts directly with the polymer chain resulting in a change in conductivity of the polymer.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] These types of systems lack selectivity due to the wide range of target molecules that can interact with the polymer.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Molecularly imprinted polymers can add selectivity to conductive polymer chemiresistors.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] A molecularly imprinted polymer is made by polymerizing a polymer around a target molecule and then removing the target molecule from the polymer leaving behind cavities matching the size and shape of the target molecule.
[src:gas-sensors/chemiresistor] Molecularly imprinting the conductive polymer increases the sensitivity of the chemiresistor by selecting for the target's general size and shape as well as its ability to interact with the chain of the conductive polymer.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] Naoyoshi Taguchi became the first person in the world to develop a semiconductor device that could detect low concentrations of combustible and reducing gases when used with a simple electrical circuit.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] Devices based on this technology are often called "TGS" (Taguchi Gas Sensors).
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] The sensors contain two or three electrodes, occasionally four, in contact with an electrolyte.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] The electrodes are typically fabricated by fixing a high surface area of precious metal onto the porous hydrophobic membrane.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] The working electrode contacts both the electrolyte and the ambient air to be monitored, usually via a porous membrane.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] The electrolyte most commonly used is a mineral acid, but organic electrolytes are also used for some sensors.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] The electrodes and housing are usually in a plastic housing which contains a gas entry hole for the gas and electrical contacts.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] The gas diffuses into the sensor, through the back of the porous membrane to the working electrode, where it is oxidized or reduced.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] This electrochemical reaction results in an electric current that passes through the external circuit.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] In addition to measuring, amplifying, and performing other signal processing functions, the external circuit maintains the voltage across the sensor between the working and counter electrodes for a two-electrode sensor or between the working and reference electrodes for a three-electrode cell.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] At the counter electrode, an equal and opposite reaction occurs, such that if the working electrode is an oxidation, then the counter electrode is a reduction.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] The magnitude of the current is controlled by how much of the target gas is oxidized at the working electrode.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] Sensors are usually designed so that the gas supply is limited by diffusion, and thus the output from the sensor is linearly proportional to the gas concentration.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] This linear output is one of the advantages of electrochemical sensors over other sensor technologies (e.g. infrared), whose output must be linearized before they can be used.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] A linear output allows for more precise measurement of low concentrations and much simpler calibration (only a baseline and one point are needed).
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] Diffusion control offers another advantage.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] Changing the diffusion barrier allows the sensor manufacturer to tailor the sensor to a particular target gas concentration range.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] In addition, since the diffusion barrier is primarily mechanical, the calibration of electrochemical sensors tends to be more stable over time and so electrochemical sensor-based instruments require much less maintenance than some other detection technologies.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] In principle, the sensitivity can be calculated based on the diffusion properties of the gas path into the sensor, though experimental errors in the measurement of the diffusion properties make the calculation less accurate than calibrating with test gas.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] For some gases, such as ethylene oxide, cross-sensitivity can be a problem because ethylene oxide requires a very active working electrode catalyst and high operating potential for its oxidation.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] Therefore, gases that are more easily oxidized, such as alcohols and carbon monoxide will also give a response.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] Cross-sensitivity problems can be eliminated through the use of a chemical filter, for example, filters that allow the target gas to pass through unimpeded but which reacts with and removes common interferences.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] While electrochemical sensors offer many advantages, they are not suitable for every gas.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] Sensors for carbon dioxide are an example of this approach and they have been commercially available for several years.
[src:gas-sensors/electrochemical-gas-sensor] Cross-sensitivity of electronic chemical sensors may also be utilized to design chemical sensor arrays, which utilize a variety of specific sensors that are cross-reactive for fingerprint detection of target gases in complex mixtures.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] A **gas detector** is a device that detects the presence of gases in a volume of space, often as part of a safety system.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] A gas detector can sound an alarm to operators in the area where the leak is occurring, giving them the opportunity to leave.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] This type of device is important because there are many gases that can be harmful to organic life, such as humans or animals.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Gas detectors can be used to detect combustible, flammable and toxic gases, and oxygen depletion.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] This type of device is used widely in industry and can be found in locations, such as on oil rigs, to monitor manufacturing processes and emerging technologies such as photovoltaic.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Gas leak detection methods became a concern after the effects of harmful gases on human health were discovered.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Before modern electronic sensors, early detection methods relied on less precise detectors.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Through the 19th and early 20th centuries, coal miners would bring canaries down to the tunnels with them as an early detection system against life-threatening gases such as carbon dioxide, carbon monoxide and methane.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The canary, normally a very songful bird, would stop singing and eventually die if not removed from these gases, signaling the miners to exit the mine quickly.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The first gas detector in the industrial age was the *flame safety lamp* (or Davy lamp) was invented by Sir Humphry Davy (of England) in 1815 to detect the presence of methane (firedamp) in underground coal mines.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The flame safety lamp consisted of an oil flame adjusted to specific height in fresh air.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] To prevent ignition with these lamps the flame was contained within a glass sleeve with a mesh flame arrestor.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The flames height varied depending on the presence of methane (higher) or the lack of oxygen (lower).
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] To this day, in certain parts of the world flame safety lamps are still in service.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The modern era of gas detection started in 1926–1927 with the development of the catalytic combustion (LEL) sensor by Dr.Oliver Johnson.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Dr Johnson was an employee of Standard Oil Company in California (now Chevron), he began research and development on a method to detect combustible mixtures in air to help prevent explosions in fuel storage tanks.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] A demonstration model was developed in 1926 and denoted as the Model A.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The first practical "electric vapor indicator" meter begun production in 1927 with the release of the Model B.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The world's first gas detection company, Johnson-Williams Instruments (or J-W Instruments) was formed in 1928 in Palo Alto, CA by Dr Oliver Johnson and Phil Williams.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] J-W Instruments is recognized as the first electronics company in Silicon Valley.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Before the development of electronic household carbon monoxide detectors in the 1980s and 1990s, carbon monoxide presence was detected with a chemically infused paper that turned brown when exposed to the gas.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Since then, many electronic technologies and devices have been developed to detect, monitor, and alert the leak of a wide array of gases.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] As the cost and performance of electronic gas sensors improved, they have been incorporated into a wider range of systems.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Their use in automobiles was initially for engine emissions control, but now gas sensors may also be used to ensure passenger comfort and safety.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Carbon dioxide sensors are being installed into buildings as part of demand-controlled ventilation systems.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Sophisticated gas sensor systems are being researched for use in medical diagnostic, monitoring, and treatment systems, well beyond their initial use in operating rooms.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Gas monitors and alarms for carbon monoxide and other harmful gases are increasingly available for office and domestic use, and are becoming legally required in some jurisdictions.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Originally, detectors were produced to detect a single gas.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Modern units may detect several toxic or combustible gases, or even a combination.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Newer gas analyzers can break up the component signals from a complex aroma to identify several gases simultaneously.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) sensors were introduced in the 1990s.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The earliest known MOS gas sensor was demonstrated by G.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] MOS sensors have since become important environmental gas detectors.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Gas detectors can be classified according to the operation mechanism (semiconductor, oxidation, catalytic, photoionization, infrared, etc.).
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Gas detectors come packaged into two main form factors: portable devices and fixed gas detectors.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Portable detectors are used to monitor the atmosphere around personnel and are either hand-held or worn on clothing or on a belt/harness.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] These gas detectors are usually battery operated.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] They transmit warnings via audible and visible signals, such as alarms and flashing lights, when dangerous levels of gas vapors are detected.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Fixed type gas detectors may be used for detection of one or more gas types.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Fixed type detectors are generally mounted near the process area of a plant or control room, or an area to be protected, such as a residential bedroom.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Generally, industrial sensors are installed on fixed type mild steel structures and a cable connects the detectors to a supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA) system for continuous monitoring.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] A tripping interlock can be activated for an emergency situation.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Electrochemical gas detectors work by allowing gases to diffuse through a porous membrane to an electrode where it is either chemically oxidized or reduced.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The amount of current produced is determined by how much of the gas is oxidized at the electrode, indicating the concentration of the gas.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Manufactures can customize electrochemical gas detectors by changing the porous barrier to allow for the detection of a certain gas concentration range.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Also, since the diffusion barrier is a physical/mechanical barrier, the detectors tend to be more stable and reliable over the sensor's duration and thus required less maintenance than other early detector technologies.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] However, the sensors are subject to corrosive elements or chemical contamination and may last only 1–2 years before a replacement is required.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Electrochemical gas detectors are used in a wide variety of environments such as refineries, gas turbines, chemical plants, underground gas storage facilities, and more.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Catalytic bead (pellistor) sensors are commonly used to measure combustible gases that present an explosion hazard when concentrations are between the lower explosion limit (LEL) and upper explosion limit (UEL).
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Active and reference beads containing platinum wire coils are situated on opposite arms of a Wheatstone bridge circuit and electrically heated, up to a few hundred degrees C.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The active bead contains a catalyst that allows combustible compounds to oxidize, thereby heating the bead even further and changing its electrical resistance.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The resulting voltage difference between the active and passive beads is proportional to the concentration of all combustible gases and vapors present.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The sampled gas enters the sensor through a sintered metal frit, which provides a barrier to prevent an explosion when the instrument is carried into an atmosphere containing combustible gases.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Pellistors measure essentially all combustible gases, but they are more sensitive to smaller molecules that diffuse through the sinter more quickly.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The measurable concentration ranges are typically from a few hundred ppm to a few volume percent.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Such sensors are inexpensive and robust, but require a minimum of a few percent oxygen in the atmosphere to be tested and they can be poisoned or inhibited by compounds such as silicones, mineral acids, chlorinated organic compounds, and sulfur compounds.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Photoionization detectors (PIDs) use a high-photon-energy UV lamp to ionize chemicals in the sampled gas.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] If the compound has an ionization energy below that of the lamp photons, an electron will be ejected, and the resulting current is proportional to the concentration of the compound.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Common lamp photon energies include 10.0 eV, 10.6 eV and 11.7 eV; the standard 10.6 eV lamp lasts for years, while the 11.7 eV lamp typically last only a few months and is used only when no other option is available.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] A broad range of compounds can be detected at levels ranging from a few parts per billion (ppb) to several thousand parts per million (ppm).
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Detectable compound classes in order of decreasing sensitivity include: aromatics and alkyl iodides; olefins, sulfur compounds, amines, ketones, ethers, alkyl bromides and silicate esters; organic esters, alcohols, aldehydes and alkanes; hydrogen sulfide, ammonia, phosphine and organic acids.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] There is no response to standard components of air or to mineral acids.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Major advantages of PIDs are their excellent sensitivity and simplicity of use; the main limitation is that measurements are not compound-specific.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Recently PIDs with pre-filter tubes have been introduced that enhance the specificity for such compounds as benzene or butadiene.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Fixed, hand-held and miniature clothing-clipped PIDs are widely used for industrial hygiene, hazmat, and environmental monitoring.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Infrared (IR) point sensors use radiation passing through a known volume of gas; energy from the sensor beam is absorbed at certain wavelengths, depending on the properties of the specific gas.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] For example, carbon monoxide absorbs wavelengths of about 4.2-4.5 μm.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The energy in this wavelength is compared to a wavelength outside of the absorption range; the difference in energy between these two wavelengths is proportional to the concentration of gas present.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] This type of sensor is advantageous because it does not have to be placed into the gas to detect it and can be used for remote sensing.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Infrared point sensors can be used to detect hydrocarbons and other infrared active gases such as water vapor and carbon dioxide.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] IR sensors are commonly found in waste-water treatment facilities, refineries, gas turbines, chemical plants, and other facilities where flammable gases are present and the possibility of an explosion exists.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The remote sensing capability allows large volumes of space to be monitored.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Engine emissions are another area where IR sensors are being researched.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The sensor would detect high levels of carbon monoxide or other abnormal gases in vehicle exhaust and even be integrated with vehicle electronic systems to notify drivers.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Infrared image sensors include active and passive systems.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] For active sensing, IR imaging sensors typically scan a laser across the field of view of a scene and look for backscattered light at the absorption line wavelength of a specific target gas.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Passive IR imaging sensors measure spectral changes at each pixel in an image and look for specific spectral signatures that indicate the presence of target gases.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The types of compounds that can be imaged are the same as those that can be detected with infrared point detectors, but the images may be helpful in identifying the source of a gas.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Semiconductor gas sensors, most commonly metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) sensors, detect gases by a chemical reaction that takes place when the gas comes in direct contact with the surface of the sensing element, which is usually heated to temperatures between 200 °C and 500 °C.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Tin dioxide is the most common material used in semiconductor gas sensors, and the electrical resistance in the sensor is decreased when it comes in contact with the monitored gas.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The resistance of the tin dioxide layer, typically in the range of 10 to 500 kΩ in air, can drop to a small fraction of this value in the presence of a reducing gas.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] This change in resistance (often together with signals of other sensors, e.g. humidity sensor values, for cross-sensitivity compensation) is used to calculate the gas concentration.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Semiconductor gas sensors are commonly used to detect hydrogen, alcohol vapor, and harmful gases such as carbon monoxide.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] One of the most common uses for semiconductor gas sensors is in carbon monoxide sensors.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Because the sensor must come in contact with the gas to detect it, semiconductor gas sensors work over a smaller distance than infrared point or ultrasonic detectors.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] MOS sensors can detect different gases, such as carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, hydrogen sulfide, and ammonia.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Since the 1990s, MOS sensors have become important environmental gas detectors.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] MOS sensors although very versatile, suffer from the problem of cross sensitivity with humidity and other gases.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The cause for humidity cross-sensitivity has been attributed to interaction of hydroxyl ions with the oxide surface.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Such interferences can be reduced using algorithmic optimizations and temperature-cycled operation.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Ultrasonic gas leak detectors are not gas detectors per se.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] They detect the acoustic emission created when a pressured gas expands in a low pressure area through a small orifice (the leak).
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] They use acoustic sensors to detect changes in the background noise of its environment.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Since most high-pressure gas leaks generate sound in the ultrasonic range of 25 kHz to 10 MHz, the sensors are able to easily distinguish these frequencies from background acoustic noise which occurs in the audible range of 20 Hz to 20 kHz.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The ultrasonic gas leak detector then produces an alarm when there is an ultrasonic deviation from the normal condition of background noise.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Ultrasonic gas leak detectors cannot measure gas concentration, but the device is able to determine the leak rate of an escaping gas because the ultrasonic sound level depends on the gas pressure and size of the leak.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Ultrasonic gas detectors are mainly used for remote sensing in outdoor environments where weather conditions can easily dissipate escaping gas before allowing it to reach leak detectors that require contact with the gas to detect it and sound an alarm.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] These detectors are commonly found on offshore and onshore oil/gas platforms, gas compressor and metering stations, gas turbine power plants, and other facilities that house a lot of outdoor pipeline.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Holographic gas sensors use light reflection to detect changes in a polymer film matrix containing a hologram.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Since holograms reflect light at certain wavelengths, a change in their composition can generate a colorful reflection indicating the presence of a gas molecule.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] However, holographic sensors require illumination sources such as white light or lasers, and an observer or CCD detector.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] All gas detectors must be calibrated on a schedule.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Of the two form factors of gas detectors, portables must be calibrated more frequently due to the regular changes in environment they experience.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] A typical calibration schedule for a fixed system may be quarterly, bi-annually or even annually with more robust units.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] A typical calibration schedule for a portable gas detector is a daily "bump test" accompanied by a monthly calibration.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Almost every portable gas detector requires a specific calibration gas In the US, the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) may set minimum standards for periodic recalibration.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Because a gas detector is used for employee/worker safety, it is very important to make sure it is operating to manufacturer's specifications.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Australian standards specify that a person operating any gas detector is strongly advised to check the gas detector's performance each day and that it is maintained and used in accordance with the manufacturers instructions and warnings.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] A challenge test should consist of exposing the gas detector to a known concentration of gas to ensure that the gas detector will respond and that the audible and visual alarms activate.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] It is also important to inspect the gas detector for any accidental or deliberate damage by checking that the housing and screws are intact to prevent any liquid ingress and that the filter is clean, all of which can affect the functionality of the gas detector.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The basic calibration or challenge test kit will consist of calibration gas/regulator/calibration cap and hose (generally supplied with the gas detector) and a case for storage and transport.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Because 1 in every 2,500 untested instruments will fail to respond to a dangerous concentration of gas, many large businesses use an automated test/calibration station for bump tests and calibrate their gas detectors daily.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Oxygen deficiency gas monitors are used for employee and workforce safety.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Cryogenic substances such as liquid nitrogen (LN2), liquid helium (He), and liquid argon (Ar) are inert and can displace oxygen (O2) in a confined space if a leak is present.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] A rapid decrease of oxygen can provide a very dangerous environment for employees, who may not notice this problem before they suddenly lose consciousness.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] With this in mind, an oxygen gas monitor is important to have when cryogenics are present.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Laboratories, MRI rooms, pharmaceutical, semiconductor, and cryogenic suppliers are typical users of oxygen monitors.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Oxygen fraction in a breathing gas is measured by electro-galvanic oxygen sensors.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] They may be used stand-alone, for example to determine the proportion of oxygen in a nitrox mixture used in scuba diving, or as part of feedback loop which maintains a constant partial pressure of oxygen in a rebreather.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Gaseous ammonia is continuously monitored in industrial refrigeration processes and biological degradation processes, including exhaled breath.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Depending on the required sensitivity, different types of sensors are used (e.g., flame ionization detector, semiconductor, electrochemical, photonic membranes).
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Detectors usually operate near the lower exposure limit of 25ppm; however, ammonia detection for industrial safety requires continuous monitoring above the fatal exposure limit of 0.1%.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Hydrogen is a highly explosive material when its concentration exceed 4%, making it a safety hazard.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] It is therefore crucial to monitor its concentration continuously.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Developing highly sensitive and reliable hydrogen gas sensors is crucial for early detection, enabling real-time monitoring and triggering alarms before dangerous concentrations are reached.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] These sensors play a critical role in ensuring the safe use of hydrogen across various applications, from fuel cells to industrial processes.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Many sensor candidates have been suggested including electrical, optical, acoustical...
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The main principle behind hydrogen gas sensors is to integrate a catalytic material that undergoes changes in its physical properties when exposed to hydrogen.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] These changes can manifest in various ways, such as shifts in the material's **work function** or alterations in its **surface plasmon resonance**.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Catalytic materials like **Palladium** and **Platinum** are commonly used due to their high sensitivity to hydrogen.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] When hydrogen molecules interact with these metals, they dissociate and are absorbed, causing changes in electrical or optical characteristics.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] These shifts are then detected and translated into a measurable signal, allowing for the accurate monitoring of hydrogen concentrations in real-time.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] There are several different sensors that can be installed to detect hazardous gases in a residence.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Carbon monoxide is a very dangerous, but odorless, colorless gas, making it difficult for humans to detect.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Carbon monoxide detectors can be purchased for around US$20–60.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Many local jurisdictions in the United States now require installation of carbon monoxide detectors in addition to smoke detectors in residences.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] Handheld flammable gas detectors can be used to trace leaks from natural gas lines, propane tanks, butane tanks, or any other combustible gas.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] These sensors can be purchased for US$35–100.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] The European Community has supported research called the MINIGAS project that was coordinated by VTT Technical Research Center of Finland.
[src:gas-sensors/gas-detector] This research project aims to develop new types of photonics-based gas sensors, and to support the creation of smaller instruments with equal or higher speed and sensitivity than conventional laboratory-grade gas detectors.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] A **nondispersive infrared sensor** (or **NDIR sensor**) is a simple spectroscopic sensor often used as a gas detector.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] It is non-dispersive in the sense that no dispersive element (e.g., a prism, or diffraction grating, as is often present in other spectrometers) is used to separate (like a monochromator) the broadband light into a narrow spectrum suitable for gas sensing.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] The majority of NDIR sensors use a broadband lamp source and an optical filter to select a narrow band spectral region that correspond to the absorption region of the gas of interest.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] In this context, the narrow band can be 50-300 nm bandwidth.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] Modern NDIR sensors may use microelectromechanical systems (MEMs) or mid IR LED sources, with or without an optical filter.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] The main components of an NDIR sensor are an infrared (IR) source (lamp), a sample chamber or light tube, a light filter and an infrared detector.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] The IR light is directed through the sample chamber towards the detector.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] In parallel there is another chamber with an enclosed reference gas, typically nitrogen.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] The gas in the sample chamber causes absorption of specific wavelengths according to the Beer–Lambert law, and the attenuation of these wavelengths is measured by the detector to determine the gas concentration.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] The detector has an optical filter in front of it that eliminates all light except the wavelength that the selected gas molecules can absorb.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] Ideally, other gas molecules do not absorb light at this wavelength, and do not affect the amount of light reaching the detector; however some cross-sensitivity is inevitable.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] For instance, many measurements in the IR area are cross sensitive to H2O so gases like CO2, SO2 and NO2 often initiate cross sensitivity in low concentrations.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] The IR signal from the source is usually chopped or modulated so that thermal background signals can be offset from the desired signal.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] NDIR sensors for carbon dioxide are often installed in heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) units.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] Configurations with multiple filters, either on individual sensors or on a rotating wheel, allow simultaneous measurement at several selected wavelengths.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR), a more complex technology, scans a wide part of the spectrum, measuring many absorbing species simultaneously.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] Miniature IR sources based on microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) have been experimentally applied to NDIR systems since 2006 and are useful since 2016.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] The low energy of MEMS emission means a sensitive detector circuit based on lock-in amplification is needed.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] Other useful detectors include the photoacoustic gas sensor which use a MEMS microphone to detect IR-gas interactions.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] Gases do not have a specific sensing wavelength, rather there are regions of the IR spectrum where there are typically many thousands of closely spaced absorption lines.
[src:gas-sensors/nondispersive-infrared-sensor] See the Hitran database for more information.
